               <head>Akbarnāmah. Vol. 1 by Abū al-Faz̤l ibn Mubārak</head>

               <msContents class="http://id.loc.gov/authorities/names/n80002413 
                  http://id.loc.gov/authorities/subjects/sh85064913 
                  http://id.loc.gov/authorities/subjects/sh2008115921 
                  http://id.loc.gov/authorities/subjects/sh2008115920">

                  <summary>Part one of the first book of the <title>Akbarnāmah</title> by Abū
                     al-Faz̤l ibn Mubārak. </summary>

                  <msItem xml:id="Uk_IO_Islamic_3308-item1">
                     <author key="viaf_5150639">
                        <persName xml:lang="fa-Latn-x-lc">Abū al-Faz̤l ibn Mubārak,
                           1551-1602</persName>
                        <persName xml:lang="fa">أبو الفضل بن مبارك</persName>
                     </author>
                     <title xml:lang="fa-Latn-x-lc" key="work_20880">Akbarnāmah</title>
                     <title xml:lang="fa">اكبرنامه</title>
                     <incipit xml:lang="fa">(f. 1v, basmala) الله اكبر اين جه دريافتیست ثرف وشناختی
                        ...</incipit>
                     <note>This copy lacks all headings. </note>
                     <textLang mainLang="fa">Persian</textLang>
                  </msItem>
               </msContents>
               <physDesc>
                  <objectDesc form="codex">
                     <supportDesc material="chart">
                        <extent>ff. 260 <dimensions type="leaf" unit="mm">
                              <height>273</height>
                              <width>165</width>
                           </dimensions>
                        </extent>
                        <foliation>
                           <p>European numerals pencilled on every fifth folio. </p>
                        </foliation>
                        <condition>
                           <p>Fair.</p>
                        </condition>
                     </supportDesc>
                     <layoutDesc>
                        <layout columns="1" ruledLines="19">
                           <p>19 lines per page. </p>
                        </layout>
                     </layoutDesc>
                  </objectDesc>
                  <handDesc>
                     <summary/>
                     <handNote>
                        <p>Nastaʻlīq; copied in black ink, with markings and overlinings in red.
                        </p>
                     </handNote>
                  </handDesc>
                  <additions>
                     <p>Folio 1r contains the following seals and inscriptions:</p>
                     <list type="bulleted">
                        <item>An acquisition note of a former owner dated 22 Shaʻban 1164 (16 July
                           1751) signed by ‘the most insignificant of the servants of God, the
                           Mighty — son of the late Murtazā al‑Ḥusaynī al‑Ṭannūrī?,’ adjacent to his
                           rectangular seal: <hi rend="italic">Muḥammad Ibrāhīm al-Ḥusaynī 1150</hi>
                           (1737/38). </item>
                        <item>Statement of purchase of former owner Abū’l-Muḥsin on 6 Muḥarram year
                           19 (6 May 1737) accompanied by his rectangular seal dated 1183 (1769/70)
                           and his personal talismanic cypher. Abū’l-Muḥsin owned several manuscripts in the Johnson collection. </item>
                        <item>Richard Johnson's accession statement: <hi rend="italic">kitāb-i
                              sarkār Navvāb Mumtāz al-Dawlah Mufakhkhar al-Mulk Ḥusām Jang Mistar
                              Richārd Jānsan Ṣāḥib Bahādur dām iqbāluh. </hi></item>
                        <item>A further erased illegible inscription, possibly belonging with the
                           octagonal seal (see below) of 1141 (1728/29). </item>
                     </list>
                     <p>Pastedown includes affixed bookplate of <orgName role="fmo"
                           key="viaf_125587814">East India College</orgName> inscribed ‘AUSPICIO
                        REGIS ET SENATUS ANGLIAE’. </p>
                     <p>A flyleaf records the East India College Library shelfmark as 14.J.3</p>
                  </additions>
                  <bindingDesc>
                     <binding notBefore="1875" notAfter="1899">
                        <decoNote>Late 19th century full mottled leather covering on plain boards. 
                        </decoNote>
                     </binding>
                  </bindingDesc>
                  <sealDesc>
                     <seal subtype="octagon" type="stamp">
                        <p>Octagonal devotional seal of unidentified former owner, probably named
                           Raḥmān (f. 1r): <hi rend="italic">Bi’smi’llāh al-raḥman al-raḥīm
                              1141</hi> (1728/29). </p>
                     </seal>
                     <seal subtype="rectangle" type="stamp">
                        <p>Rectangular seal of former owner (f. 1r): <hi rend="italic"><persName role="fmo" key="person_f8877">Muḥammad
                              Ibrāhīm al-Ḥusaynī</persName> 1150</hi> (1737/38). </p>
                     </seal>
                     <seal subtype="rectangle" type="stamp">
                        <p>Rectangular seal of former owner (f. 1r): <hi rend="italic">Abū’l-Muḥsin
                              1183</hi> (1769/70). </p>
                     </seal>
                  </sealDesc>
               </physDesc>
               <history>
                  <origin><origDate calendar="#Gregorian" notBefore="1700" notAfter="1790">Undated.
                        18th century</origDate>
                     <origPlace>India</origPlace>
                  </origin>
                  <provenance>
                     <p>Acquired possibly by <persName role="fmo" key="person_f8877">Muḥammad Ibrāhīm
                           al-Ḥusaynī</persName> — his seal dated 1150 (1737/38) on 22 Shaʻban 1164
                        (16 July 1751). </p>
                     <p>Subsequently owned by <persName role="fmo" key="person_f8878">Abū’l-Muḥsin</persName> —
                        his seal dated 1183 (1769/70). </p>
                     <p>Acquired in India between 1770 and 1790 by East India Company servant
                           <persName role="fmo" key="viaf_287207857">Richard Johnson</persName>, and
                        brought to England on his return. </p>
                  </provenance>
                  <acquisition>
                     <p>The collection of <persName role="fmo" key="viaf_287207857">Richard
                           Johnson</persName>—comprising 64 albums of paintings and an estimated
                        1,000 manuscripts—was purchased by the East India Company Library for 3,000
                        guineas on <date calendar="#Gregorian" when="1807-02-18">18 February
                           1807</date>. </p>
                     <p>This manuscript was one of many which were deposited with East India College
                        at Haileybury and received back in 1860 after the College had closed. </p>
                  </acquisition>
               </history>
